The {{nihongo|'''Okameishi Kofun'''|お亀石古墳|}} is a [[Kofun period]] square-shaped [[kofun|Kofun]], located in the Nakano neighborhood of the city of [[Tondabayashi, Osaka]] in the [[Kansai region]] of [[Japan]]. The tumulus was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 2002 collectively with the nearby [[Shindō temple ruins]] and the Oganji-ike tile kiln ruins.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/401/3348 |title=新堂廃寺跡 附オガンジ池瓦窯跡 お亀石古墳|trans-title=Shindo temple ruins with Oganji-ike tile kiln ruins and Okameishi Kofun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2021}}</ref>
==Overview== The Okameishi Kofun is a {{nihongo|''{{ill|Square Kofun|lt=hōfun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}-style tumulus with 21-meter square sides. It is located on a ridge that protrudes southeast from the Habino Hills at an elevation of 98 meters. No ''[[fukiishi]]'' have been found at the site.The tumulus is orientated to the south and has a horizontal grantite-lined [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] containing a house-shaped sarcophagus.The sarcophagus is made of white [[tuff]] from [[Mount Nijō]] and has a stone lid with six protrusions for hanging by ropes. As the lid has been exposed for a long time it has weathered and resembles the shape of a turtle, hence the name "Kameishi". An [[archaeological excavation]] in 2002 revealed that the entourage was originally closed with a river stone. [[:en:Burial goods|Burial goods]] included shards of [[Sue pottery]] pottery, which date the tumulus to the first half of the 7th century. An unusual feature is that many flat [[roof tile]]s from the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]] are stacked up around the sarcophagus forming a retaining wall. The tiles are the same type as the [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]]-style roof tiles used at the Shindō temple ruins located to the southeast, and may indicate that the person buried in this time had some close relationship with that temple.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=978-4311750403}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The tumulus is about a 15-minute walk from [[Tondabayashi Station]] on the [[Kintetsu Nagano Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
