==Overview== The Okameishi Kofun is a {{nihongo|''{{ill|Square Kofun|lt=hōfun|ja|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Square Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|方墳|1=Square Kofun|1=Square Kofun}}-style tumulus with 21-meter square sides. It is located on a ridge that protrudes southeast from the Habino Hills at an elevation of 98 meters. No ''[[fukiishi]]'' have been found at the site.The tumulus is orientated to the south and has a horizontal grantite-lined [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] containing a house-shaped sarcophagus.The sarcophagus is made of white [[tuff]] from [[:en:Mount Nijō|Mount Nijō]] and has a stone lid with six protrusions for hanging by ropes. As the lid has been exposed for a long time it has weathered and resembles the shape of a turtle, hence the name "Kameishi". An [[archaeological excavation]] in 2002 revealed that the entourage was originally closed with a river stone. [[:en:Burial goods|Burial goods]] included shards of [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] pottery, which date the tumulus to the first half of the 7th century. An unusual feature is that many flat [[:en:Roof tile|Roof tile]]s from the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]] are stacked up around the sarcophagus forming a retaining wall. The tiles are the same type as the [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]]-style roof tiles used at the Shindō temple ruins located to the southeast, and may indicate that the person buried in this time had some close relationship with that temple.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=978-4311750403}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The tumulus is about a 15-minute walk from [[Tondabayashi Station]] on the [[:en:Kintetsu Nagano Line|Kintetsu Nagano Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
